      • contains

        public final boolean contains(String string)
        Description copied from interface: Container
        Check the existence of some give string based term with prolog syntax in this Container. The string based term will be parsed and the internal term representation query to the prolog engine. The contention concept is base on the prolog clause/2 built-in on instance prolog engine. The clause/2 check that exist some clause in the prolog program or database which unifies your head and your body. The clause/2 is based on terms unification and make more flexible the contention concept. If clause/2 success then in the prolog program/database some define clause match with converted object and can be resolved. If clause/2 fail then in the prolog program/database no one clause exist that resolve the converted object. 
         objectContainer.contains("'io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'(Idp, X, Y)");
 objectContainer.contains("'io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( a, 3,14 )");
        Formulated Prolog Query 
         ?- clause('io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( Idp, X, Y ),true).
 ?- clause('io.github.prolobjectlink.domain.geometry.Point'( a, 3,14 ),true).
        Specified by:
        contains in interface Container
        Parameters:
        string - string based prolog term.
        Returns:
        true if string based term is defined in this Container, false otherwise.
        See Also:
        Container.contains(Object), Container.contains(Class), Container.contains(Predicate), Container.contains(String, int)

      • contains

        public final boolean contains(String f,
                              int a)
        Description copied from interface: Container
        Check the existence of prolog predicates in this Container that have predicate indicator created from the given functor and arity. The contention concept is base on the prolog current_predicate/1 built-in on instanced prolog engine. The current_predicate/1 check that exist some predicate in the prolog program/database or engine defined built-ins with equals functor and arity. If current_predicate/1 success then in the prolog program/database or engine defined built-ins some define predicate match with the given functor and arity and can be resolved. If current_predicate/1 fail then in the prolog program/database or engine defined built-ins no one predicate exist.
        Specified by:

        a - predicate arity

      • createQuery

        public final Query createQuery(String string)
        Description copied from interface: PersistentContainer

        Query builded from a string with standard prolog syntax. The string query is translated to prolog terms and passed to the prolog engine for to be resolved. The predicate classes present in the prolog string will be store for resolve and return instances of those classes as result of querying and build predicates classes from result obtained of the prolog engine. 

         query = pm.createQuery("point(Idp, X, Y)");
 query = pm.createQuery("segment(Ids, Point0, Point1)");

        The string query allow the arithmetic comparison and term comparison but this operators will not be resolve to predicate classes. Only will be resolve predicate class that was specified in the configuration. 

         query = pm.createQuery("point(Idp, X, Y), X =:= 3, Y =:= 14");
 query = pm.createQuery("segment(Ids, Point0, Point1), Point0 == point(a, 3,14), Point1 == point(b, 3,14)");

        This query variant support the projection that is the presence of various predicate classes in the prolog string query. 

         query = pm.createQuery("point(Idp, X, Y), segment(Ids, Point0, Point1)");

        Waring with equals variables in different class. This cause that in the translated prolog query this variables can be instantiated with a value that not is the same expected value for different predicate classes or not return the expected query result.

        Specified by:
        createQuery in interface PersistentContainer
        Parameters:
        string - string with standard prolog syntax.
        Returns:
        Query builded from a string with standard prolog syntax.

      • createQuery

        public final <O> TypedQuery<O> createQuery(O o)
        Description copied from interface: PersistentContainer

        Query by Example implementation. This query is builded from a template Object object obtaining from this term the most general prolog Object term using reflection and and passed to the predicate context for to be resolved. In most general Object (or predicate) resolution the values of the fields are conserved and fields with null values are substituting by the variable name specified on field argument annotations. This process is named inspection. The inspection process find three variants for resolve the term to query.

        If the Object term are fully instantiated only one solution is possible and will be a new Object term obtained from the predicate context that is equals to the template object. 

         query = pm.createQuery(new Point(new Atom("a"), new Float(3.5), new Float(10.14)));
        Prolog Generated Query: 
         ?-point(a, 3,14).

        If the Object term are fully empty (all field are null values) the query will be formulated from the most general Object term using as prolog variables names the names specified on fields arguments annotations. The solution for this query variant will be builded for all Object that match with the most general relation obtained 

         query = pm.createQuery(new Point());
 query = pm.createQuery(new Segment());
        Prolog Generated Query: 
         ?-point(Ipd, X, Y).
 ?-segment(Ips, Point0, Point1).

        If the Object term are partially instantiated/empty the query will be formulated as a combination of the two variants before mentioned. The instantiate fields preserve your values and null fields values will be replaced by your corresponded variable name. 

         
 query = pm.createQuery(new Point(new Float(3.5), new Float(10.14)));
        Prolog Generated Query: 
         ?-point(Ipd, 3,14).
        Specified by:
        createQuery in interface PersistentContainer
        Parameters:
        o - object template
        Returns:
        TypedQuery builded from a object template.

      • createQuery

        public final <O> TypedQuery<O> createQuery(Class<O> clazz)
        Description copied from interface: PersistentContainer
        Query builded from a Object class. The most general prolog Object term is obtaining and resolved. In most general Object (or predicate) resolution only terms used for build the query are the variables names specified on field argument annotations. In other words create a query from a Object class is always equivalent to query with the most general predicate. This query way will have the same result of the Query by example with an object template with fully empty. The solution for this query variant will be builded for all Object that match with the most general relation obtained 
         query = pm.createQuery(Point.class);
 query = pm.createQuery(Segment.class);
        Prolog Generated Query: 
         ?-point(Ipd, X, Y).
 ?-segment(Ips, Point0, Point1).
        Specified by:
        createQuery in interface PersistentContainer
        Parameters:
        clazz - class for build the query
        Returns:
        TypedQuery builded from a Object class
